{{short description|Series of rotary powered sports cars}}
{{Infobox automobile
| name = Mazda RX-7
| image = Tuned Mazda RX-7 Type RB (GF-FD3S) front.jpg
| caption = Mazda RX-7 Type RB (FD3S)
| manufacturer = [[Mazda]]
| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])
| production = 1978–2002<br>811,634 produced<ref name="Long">{{cite book |title=RX-7 |last=Long |first=Brian |year=2004 |publisher=Veloce Publishing |location=Dorchester |isbn=978-1-904788-03-4|page=206 }}</ref>
| assembly = Japan: [[Hiroshima]] ([[Hiroshima (Mazda factory)|Hiroshima Assembly]])
| platform = [[Mazda F platform|Mazda F]]
| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout#Front mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]
| predecessor = [[Mazda RX-3]]
| successor = [[Mazda RX-8]]
}}

The '''Mazda RX-7''' is a front/mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive, rotary engine-powered [[sports car]] that was manufactured and marketed by [[Mazda]] from 1978 to 2002 across three generations, all of which made use of a compact, lightweight [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].

The first generation of the RX-7, SA, was a two-seater 2 door [[hatchback]] [[coupé]]. It featured a 12A carbureted rotary engine as well as the option for a 13B with electronic fuel injection in later years.

The second generation of RX-7, known as the FC, was offered as a 2-seater coupé with a 2+2 option available in some markets, as well as in a convertible bodystyle. This was powered by the 13B rotary engine, offered in naturally aspirated or turbocharged forms.

The third generation of the RX-7, known as the FD, was also a 2-seater coupé. This featured a sequentially turbocharged 13B REW engine. This also featured the 2+2 seating option in some markets.

The RX-7 made ''[[Car and Driver]]'' magazine's [[Car and Driver Ten Best|Ten Best list]] five times. More than 800,000 were manufactured over its lifetime.<ref name="Long" />

