[[File:Mazda RX-7 (FD3S) rear.JPG|thumb|left|Rear view]]

The third generation RX-7, '''FD''' (chassis code FD3S for Japan and JM1FD for the North America), featured an updated body design. The 13B-REW was the first-ever mass-produced [[twin-turbo#Sequential twin-turbo|sequential twin-turbocharger]] system to be exported from Japan,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autocar.co.nz/autocar-news-app/mazda-pays-tribute-to-the-rx-7|title=Mazda pays tribute to the RX-7|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> boosting power to {{Convert|255|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} in 1993 and finally {{Convert|280|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} by the time production ended in Japan in 2002.

The chief designer was {{nihongo|Yoichi Sato|佐藤 洋一|Satō Yōichi}}.<ref name="booksample">{{cite book |last1=望月 |first1=澄男 |title=マツダRX-7 |date=2017 |publisher=Miki Press |location=Japan |isbn=978-4-89522-675-2 |pages=21 |url=http://www.mikipress.com/books/pdf/675.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219063556/http://www.mikipress.com/books/pdf/675.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2020-02-19 |language=ja}}</ref> Another key designer was Wu-huang Chin ({{lang|zh-Hant|秦無荒}}), a Taiwanese automotive artist who also worked on the [[Mazda MX-5 Miata]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Design Central |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1995-01-30-mn-26006-story.html |work=Los Angeles Times |date=30 January 1995 |quote=a concept car whose design was inked at Mazda Research & Design in Irvine in 1989. It evolved into the curvy third-generation Mazda RX-7 for the 1993 model year. The design was the work of 37-year-old Wu-Huang Chin, above, who also was a member of the Miata design team.}}</ref>

In Japan, sales were affected by this series' non-compliance with Japanese [[Vehicle size class#Japan|dimension regulations]] and Japanese buyers paid annual taxes for the car's non-compliant width. As the RX-7 was now considered an upper-level luxury sports car due to the increased width dimensions, Mazda also offered two smaller offerings, the [[Mazda MX-5 (NA)|Eunos Roadster]], and the [[Mazda MX-3|Eunos Presso]] hatchback.

The sequential twin turbocharging system, introduced in 1992, was extremely complex and was developed with the aid of [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]]. It was previously used on the exclusive-to-Japan [[Mazda Cosmo#JC|Cosmo JC Series]]. The system used two turbochargers, one to provide {{Convert|10|psi|bar||abbr=on}} of boost from 1,800&nbsp;rpm. The second turbocharger activated in the upper half of the rpm range, during full throttle acceleration &mdash; at 4,000&nbsp;rpm to maintain {{convert|10|psi|bar||abbr=on}} until redline.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evo.co.uk/mazda/rx-7|title=Mazda RX-7 FD - review, history, prices and specs|website=Evo|language=en|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> The changeover process occurred at 4,500 rpm, with a momentary dip in pressure to {{Convert|8|psi|bar||abbr=on}},<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hagerty.com/articles-videos/articles/2018/05/08/fd-mazda-rx-7-buyers-guide|title=Your definitive Mazda RX-7 FD buyer's guide {{!}} Hagerty Articles|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> and provided semi-linear acceleration from a wide torque curve throughout the entire rev range under normal operation.

Under high speed driving conditions, the changeover process produced a significant increase in power output and forced technical drivers to adjust their driving style to anticipate and mitigate any over-steer during cornering.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} The standard turbo control system used 4 control solenoids, 4 actuators, both a vacuum and pressure chamber, and several feet of preformed vacuum/pressure hoses, all of which were prone to failure in part due to complexity and the inherent high temperatures of the rotary engine.<ref name=":0" />

A special high-performance version of the RX-7 was introduced in Australia in 1995, named the '''RX-7 SP'''. This model was developed to achieve [[homologation]] for racing in the [[1995 Australian GT Production Car Series|Australian GT Production Car Series]] and the [[1995 Eastern Creek 12 Hour|Eastern Creek 12 Hour]] production car race.<ref name=SPauction>{{cite web | url = https://www.motoring.com.au/uber-rare-rx-7-at-shannons-103857/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160917181819/https://www.motoring.com.au/uber-rare-rx-7-at-shannons-103857/ | archive-date = 2016-09-17 | title = Uber rare RX-7 at Shannon's | work = motoring.com.au | publisher = carsales.com Limited | last = Robinson | first = James | date = 2016-09-16 }}</ref> An initial run of 25 cars were made, and later an extra 10 were built by Mazda due to demand.<ref name=Craigs>{{cite web | url = http://cp_www.tripod.com/rotary/pg12.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150527051009/http://cp_www.tripod.com/rotary/pg12.htm | archive-date = 2015-05-27 |title= Mazda Australia's RX7-SP and RX7-SP2 (3rd Generation RX7) | date = 2001-03-22 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The RX-7 SP was rated at {{Convert|277|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|357|Nm|lb·ft|0|abbr=on}} of torque, a substantial increase over the standard model. Other changes included a race-developed carbon fibre nose cone and rear [[spoiler (car)|spoiler]], a carbon fibre 120&nbsp;L fuel tank (as opposed to the 76&nbsp;L tank in the standard car), a 4.3:1 final drive ratio, 17-inch wheels, larger brake rotors and calipers. A "three times more efficient" intercooler, a new exhaust, and a modified [[Engine Control Unit|ECU]] were also included.<ref name=Craigs/> Weight was reduced significantly with the aid of further carbon fibre usage including lightweight vented bonnet and [[Recaro]] seats to reduce weight to 1,218&nbsp;kg (from 1,250&nbsp;kg) making this model road-going race car that matched the performance of the rival [[Porsche 993|Porsche Carrera RS Club Sport]] for the final year Mazda officially entered.<ref name=SPauction/> The formula paid off when the RX-7 SP won the [[1995 Eastern Creek 12 Hour]], giving Mazda the winning 12 hour trophy for a fourth straight year.<ref name=SPauction/> The winning car also gained a podium finish at the international tarmac rally Targa Tasmania months later. A later special version, the '''Bathurst R''', was introduced in 2001 to commemorate this victory in Japan only.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tradeuniquecars.com.au/feature-cars/1703/mazda-rx-7-type-r-bathurst-r-review|title=Mazda RX-7 Type R Bathurst R Review|work=TradeUniqueCars.com.au|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> It was based on the RX-7 Type R and 500 were built in total, featuring adjustable dampers, a carbon fibre shift knob, carbon fibre interior trim, special fog lamps and a different parking brake lever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.supercars.net/blog/2001-mazda-rx-7-type-r-bathurst-2/|title=2001 Mazda RX-7 Type R Bathurst {{!}} Review {{!}} SuperCars.net|date=2016-04-24|work=Supercars.net|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref>

[[File:Mazda RX7 engine.jpg|thumb|[[Mazda Wankel engine|Mazda 13B-REW rotary engine]].]]
In the United Kingdom, for 1992, customers were offered only one version of the FD, which was based on a combination of the US touring and the base model.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} For the following year, in a bid to speed up sales, Mazda reduced the price of the RX-7 to £25,000, down from £32,000, and refunded the difference to those who bought the car before that was announced. From 1992–1995, only 210 FD RX-7s were officially sold in the UK.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/tgs-guide-japan/mazda-rx-7-buying-guide-mk3-top-gear-japan-special#3|title=Top Gear's mk3 Mazda RX-7 buying guide|date=2018-03-12|work=Top Gear|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> The FD continued to be imported to the UK until 1996. In 1998, for a car that had suffered from slow sales when it was officially sold, with a surge of interest and the benefit of a newly introduced [[Single vehicle approval|SVA]] scheme, the FD would become so popular that there were more parallel and grey imported models brought into the country than Mazda UK had ever imported.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://garagedreams.net/history/complete-history-mazda-rx-7|title=The Complete History Of The Mazda RX-7 - Garage Dreams|date=2018-02-05|work=Garage Dreams|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref>

Information about various trims and models is listed as follows:

*Series 6 (1992–1995) was exported throughout the world and had the highest sales.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} In Japan, Mazda sold the RX-7 through its [[ɛ̃fini]] brand as the '''ɛ̃fini RX-7.''' Models in Japan included the Type S, the base model, Type R, the lightweight sports model, Type RZ, Type RB, A-spec and the Touring X, which came with a four-speed automatic transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1994/1655780/efini_rx-7_touring_x.html|title=Detailed specs review of 1994 Efini RX-7 Touring X model for Japan|website=www.automobile-catalog.com|access-date=2019-01-19}}</ref> The RX-7 was sold in 1993–1995 in the U.S. and Canada. The Series 6 was rated at {{Convert|255|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{Convert|294|Nm|lb·ft|0|abbr=on}}.
*In 1993, three North American models were offered; the "base", the touring, and the R models. The touring FD included a sunroof, fog lights, leather seats, a rear window wiper and a [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] Acoustic Wave system.<ref name=":0" /> The R (R1 in 1993 and R2 in 1994–95) models featured upgraded springs, [[ThyssenKrupp|Bilstein]] shocks, an additional engine oil cooler, an aerodynamics package comprising a front lip and rear wing, and suede seats.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.drivingline.com/articles/looking-back-driving-a-bone-stock-1993-mazda-rx-7-r1/|title=Looking Back: Driving A Bone-Stock 1993 Mazda RX-7 R1|website=DrivingLine|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref> The R2 differed from the R1 in that it had slightly softer suspension.<ref name=":0" /> In 1994, the interior received a small update to include a passenger air bag, and a PEG (performance equipment group) model was offered. This model featured leather seats and a sunroof.  It did not include the fog lights or Bose stereo of the touring package. In 1995, the touring package was replaced by the PEP (popular equipment package). The PEP package contained a rear wing, leather seats, sunroof and fog lights, but didn't have the Bose Stereo nor the rear window wiper.<ref name=":0" />
*In Europe, only 1,152 examples of the FD were sold through the official Mazda network. Only one model was available and it included twin oil-coolers, electric sunroof, cruise control and the rear storage bins in place of the back seats.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} It also has the stiffer suspension and strut braces from the R models.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} Germany topped the sales with 446 cars, while UK is second at 210 and Greece third with 168.<ref name=":1" /> The European models also received the 1994 interior facelift, with a passenger air bag.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}

